description:
This video features all MIDI files that were first included in Office 97 and later versions up to Office 2007 (any edition with Microsoft Publisher included). These could be accessed using the Clip Organizer tool or from a folder located at C:\Program Files\Microsoft Office\CLIPART\PUB60COR. 

Images are from Google searches with the "labeled for noncommercial reuse" search option enabled (this video was posted with monetization disabled).

Special thanks to MIDI's Wiki for information about these MIDI files (https://midis.fandom.com/wiki/)

comments.text:
I'm a bit confused about your question. MIDI files themselves don't contain any samples, the specific soundfont does. The MIDI file is just a sequence of instructions for what samples to synthesize through some kind of MIDI synthesizer (a computer software implementation in this case) and when.

If you wanted to know what the soundfont is, that would be Roland GS Wavetable Synth (a.k.a. Microsoft GS Wavetable Synth, the default in Windows). If you use Windows, you can just use it in a MIDI editor. For other operating systems, you'll have to find the specific sound font with your favourite search engine.

If you're talking about the origin of specific instruments for the soundfont, I'm not sure at all.
